        "text": "But we are approaching a time when a Saskatchewan government is going to take a hard look at the growing problems in rural municipalities.\n\nAdmittedly, the specific problems of McKillop — driven by an RM bumping up against urban/recreation area development — are not shared by every one of the other 294 RMs in the province. That said, it’s actually rather common to now hear stories of RM councils around the province overtaxing non-permanent residents on their recreational property.\n\nIt will now be at the capable discretion of Vern Palmer — the retired rural municipal administrator appointed by the government — to “get the RM back on track.” However, from what we now know, it’s rather obvious that affected recreational property residents on the east side of Last Mountain Lake are facing a 130-per-cent residential property hike due to decisions made by council and RM administration.\n\nWe also know that this is all coming to a head after years of animosity between McKillop councillors (four of them right now) who represent the farming portion of the RM and only two councillors elected from the greater number of lakeshore-area residents who provide 63.3 per cent of McKillop’s 2017 total municipal tax levy.\n\nIn other words, it may very well yet be demonstrated that the financial problems of the RM are directly tied to the democratic representation battle that McKillop council has been fighting.\n\nYes, this is only the fifth time in the past 20 years that the province has reached the point of having to order a formal investigation into an RM — the last being in 2014, when it was determined there was a “horrendous” conflict of interest in the RM of Sherwood, which surrounds Regina.\n\nBut with significant problems ranging from collapsing bridges in the RM of Clayton to water quality in the hamlet of Lone Rock in the RM of Wilton, there are big issues small RM councils and their administrations are not handling well.\n\nIs any individual problem in any single RM grounds for restructuring? No, it isn’t.\n\nBut accumulating RM problems are surely telling us something.\n\nMandryk is the political columnist for the Regina Leader-Post."
